unbelebter Objekte ist insbesondere dann zu rechnen, wenn Subjekt und Objekt rollensemantisch nicht distinkt sind bzw. das Objekt genauso agentivisch wie das Subjekt ist.  aWhen and why are direct objects in Spanish marked with an “a”? This study investigates this question by considering inanimate objects that are normally unmarked, but require marking when combined with a small, stable class of verbs. Presenting an analysis of semantic roles, the author shows that diffential object marking in Spanish is determined not only by nominal individualization properties such as animacy and definiteness but also by the verbal action that is expressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aSpanish languagexDirect object. 0aSpanish languagexVerb phrase. 4aBelebtheit. 4aKasus. 4aSpanisch. 4aTransitivität. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Spanish.2bisacsh  aAnimacy.  aCase.  aSpanish.  aTransitivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Linguistics and Semiotics 2000 - 2014z9783110636970oZDB-23-DLS08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Complete Package 2014z9783110369526oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2014z9783110370270oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97831103739670 cprintz978311029083740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311029097440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110290974423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110290974/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGGb2014  aZDB-23-DLSc2000d2014  aZDB-23-DSPb2014